Comment_contributor: In counting, a series is begun with keha, not sakai. The word siki, used as an Indefinite Pronoun, is the same Numeral
in beginning to count a series keha is used for ‘one,’ not sakai.
[<hanavulu>, with <n> in italics]; ten-two, not two tens
[<hanavulu>, with <n> in italics]; a Verb sara, to come to, is often introduced after ten and a hundred ... ten, two has come to it, i.e. twelve
[<hanavulu>, with <n> in italics]; i.e. two the tens, (and) it has come up to two
[<hanalatu>, with <n> in italics]; hana has same meaning of double, what ever latu may be.
